When a small group of living beings (a small population) are separated from the main population from which they originate (for example, if they move over a mountain range or river, or if they move to a new island so that it cannot easily return backwards), they often find themselves in a different environment from the one in which they were before.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so the new population will need new features or adaptations to be a powerful competitor to what it needed before.
The population of origin has not changed at all, it still needs the same adaptations.
Over time, as the new to its new environment, it begins to look less and less like the other population.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will seem so different that they can no longer be considered to belong to the same species.
We call this process “specification,” which simply means the formation of new species. Specification is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
